I'm very surprised that this was not mentioned in the video-
The fact is: Swirling salt water with 9V battery works, however it is missing one critical component...a magnet. This setup will not, as stated in the video due to conservation of momentum, cause the vortex to accelerate, and the effect is small. You can increase the effect with increased magnetic field strength, lower resistance of the fluid medium, higher current input, increased voltage without changing the resistance of the fluid medium (so long as the power source is capable of outputting the required power), or all of the above .

Magnetohydrodynamics (MHD) experimental setup:
With the magnetic field lines co-axial to the cylindrical container, one battery terminal coaxial to the cylinder and magnetic field, and the other terminal on the periphery(edge) of the conductive liquid, the conductive liquid will rotate about the magnetic axis in a particular direction that is dependent on the pole facing skyward, and the terminal at the center and periphery.

This is how a Faraday motor works, though the "fluid medium" is rigid.
